name: sawing and planing, paran치 pine, kiln dried | electricity, low voltage | Cutoff, U
description:
ecoQuery: https://ecoquery.ecoinvent.org/3.10/cutoff/dataset/2722/documentation

This dataset represents the sawing and planing of one m3 Paran치 pine logs. The inventory stems from one well-documented, large, vertically integrated sawmill.;Data on debarking and sawmilling is only available from one of the two companies. ;Due to a lack of detailed information technical drying is assumed using part of the residual wood as fuel. The energy requirements and respective wood inputs are calculated based on average European processes for softwood.;;Data on sawing the timber stems from only one of the two companies. ;[A direct activity link to forestry in BR and the transport requirements to the sawmill were added for the release of ecoinvent v3.5 to re-establish the linking found in v2.2

Sawing and planing processes starting from debarked Paran치 pine logs at sawmill in Brazil.

This activity ends with sawn and planed Paran치 pine at the sawmill. The dataset includes transportation to sawmill by lorry,  sawing into timber and technical drying.
category: C:Manufacturing/16:Manufacture of wood and of products of wood and cork, except furniture; manufacture of articles of straw and plaiting materials/161:Sawmilling and planing of wood/1610:Sawmilling and planing of wood

processDocumentation.geographyDescription: wood consumption for technical drying is estimated based on European data
processDocumentation.technologyDescription: The dataset represents average European technology regarding the energy requirements and respective wood inputs. 45% of the log input (including sapwood) is generated as a co-product partly used for technical drying and partly sold or used for energy recovery used outside this process. ;Data may vary depending on the specific sawing and drying technology and the wood density of particular logs and types of sawn timber produced,

exchanges.description:
Estimation. 45% of log input (including sapwood) is generated as co-product that is partly used for technical drying and partly sold or used for energy recovery used outside this process. 

Further reference: Bauer (2003).
